I predict that Australia will win the 2019 Cricket World Cup. They have a 30% chance of winning because they have won 5 out of 11 World Cups and have been runner-up in 2 of them despite being 5th in ODI team rankings. While England leads in ODI Team Rankings, some analysts predict that England does not have as strong of a team as some of the others and may make unnecessary mistakes during competition. In addition, England has never won the Cricket World Cup. India is 2nd in ODI team rankings and also has a strong team in addition to winning 2 of the past Cricket World Cups, but I've seen articles stating that they have some serious weaknesses. New Zealand has not won the Cricket World Cup, but has some strong team members and may eke out some surprise victories. The West Indies won the first 2 Cricket World Cups and are also a possible underdog. The other teams could win, but it is extremely unlikely.

My rankings are based off a combination of historic performance, current performance, and admittedly, personal preference. Pakistan and India are cricket heavyweights, and in a tournament format I think they have the institutional knowledge and experience to perform well. South Africa has a solid squad that I think a lot of normal cricket powerhouses could be upset by.

I put India at 55% likelihood at winning the Cricket World Cup in 2019 because of their top ranking in the ICC Test Championships which concluded last month, May 2019. India has also won two Cricket World Cups in the past making it credible that they could win again. I put Australia at 25% because although they have not been doing as well in the rankings prior to this years World Cup (ranking highest at 4th place in the ICC T201 Championship) they have won the most Cricket World Cups, a total of four wins therefore I think it is possible they could win this year. I put Pakistan at a 20% likelihood because they ranked first in the ICC T201 Championship last month, May 2019 and today, the first day of the World Cup, they beat England. Therefore, I also think it is possible Pakistan could win.

I'm definitely not an expert when it comes to cricket, so I'm really leaning heavily on the analysis of others. Looking at reports from BBC and the ICC, it seems England is the top contender to win due to a complete team overall following their early exit in 2015. Closely following them is India. South Africa, NZ, and Australia have good chances as well but roster changes have placed them at a disadvantage. Pakistan had a fairly good chance, but injuries combined with a fairly young team might rule them out. West Indies could be a dark horse, depending if they can continue to surprise. https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/48125031 https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/48478058 https://www.icc-cricket.com/rankings/mens/team-rankings/odi

There have been a total 11 ICC World Cup tournaments, since 1975 and the matches occur generally every four years. Australia has won the title 5 times (has won the championship 45% of the time). Australia has additionally played in 7 of the 11 championship matches (loss ration of 28%). On the other hand, England has been to the final 3 times, however has not won it. The West Indies also won the ICC World Cup twice (has won the championship 18% of the time). As such, I believe that Australia has the biggest chance of winning the match because of its history of winning and near 33% of appearing in the final match). Even though the West Indies, Sri Lanka, and Pakistan have won the championship match, they have not done so since 1996. Australia has more recently won the cup consecutively, while India beat Sri Lanka in 2011. Afghanistan, Bangladesh and South Africa have never been in the final match. India and Sri Lanka have been traded off in regard to being in the final match recently, however Sri Lanka has not won the final match since 1996. For most of my percents, I calculated the number of times the country has been in the final match regardless if they won or not, and divided it by 24- representing the number of final matches, including the 2019 match.

I have never watched a second of cricket in my life so my forecast should be taken with a large grain of salt. I am most concerned about giving only a 10% chance to defending champion Australia. Bookmakers are favoring England, who is both the host country and the highest-ranked team in ODI cricket. England has broke the record for the ODI team total twice since 2015. India reached the 2017 ICC Champions final in 2017 and are ranked second in ODI cricket. Defending champion Australia has returned two stars that have been dealing with injury that should bring with them more offense.
